The paper proposes a new parameter estimation technique for probabilistic models, which is a common topic in machine learning. The technique is based on establishing dynamics that transform the observed data distribution into the model distribution, which suggests a connection to topics such as stochastic processes and information theory. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also mentions deep belief networks and independent component analysis, which are specific models used in neural networks, so cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is also a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the performance of the proposed technique compared to existing methods, which suggests a connection to optimization and statistics, making cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) a possible sub-category as well.
